"Chen Y.W., Prange J.D., Dühnen S., Park Y., Gunji M., Chidsey C.E.D., McIntyre P.C.","Atomic layer-deposited tunnel oxide stabilizes silicon photoanodes for water oxidation",2011,"Nature Materials","10","7",,"539","544",,,10.1038/nmat3047,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959495747&partnerID=40&md5=7b827453c4b582b7d3a34d6b4dfe8dc5","Department of Materials Science and Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Department of Chemistry, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States","Chen, Y.W., Department of Materials Science and Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Prange, J.D., Department of Chemistry, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Dühnen, S., Department of Chemistry, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Park, Y., Department of Materials Science and Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Gunji, M., Department of Materials Science and Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Chidsey, C.E.D., Department of Chemistry, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; McIntyre, P.C., Department of Materials Science and Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States","A leading approach for large-scale electrochemical energy production with minimal global-warming gas emission is to use a renewable source of electricity, such as solar energy, to oxidize water, providing the abundant source of electrons needed in fuel synthesis. We report corrosion-resistant, nanocomposite anodes for the oxidation of water required to produce renewable fuels. Silicon, an earth-abundant element and an efficient photovoltaic material, is protected by atomic layer deposition (ALD) of a highly uniform, 2g nm thick layer of titanium dioxide (TiO2) and then coated with an optically transmitting layer of a known catalyst (3 nm iridium). Photoelectrochemical water oxidation was observed to occur below the reversible potential whereas dark electrochemical water oxidation was found to have low-to-moderate overpotentials at all pH values, resulting in an inferred photovoltage of ∼550 mV. Water oxidation is sustained at these anodes for many hours in harsh pH and oxidative environments whereas comparable silicon anodes without the TiO2 coating quickly fail. The desirable electrochemical efficiency and corrosion resistance of these anodes is made possible by the low electron-tunnelling resistance (&lt;0.006 Ω cm2 for p + -Si) and uniform thickness of atomic-layer deposited TiO 2. © 2011 Macmillan Publishers Limited. All rights reserved.",,"Corrosion-resistant; Electrochemical energy; Over potential; Oxidative environment; pH value; Photo-anodes; Photo-voltage; Photoelectrochemical water oxidation; Photovoltaic materials; Renewable fuels; Renewable sources; Reversible potential; Silicon anode; Source of electrons; Thick layers; TiO; Tunnel oxides; Water oxidation; Anodes; Atomic layer deposition; Atoms; Corrosion resistance; Gas emissions; Iridium; Lead oxide; Nanocomposites; Solar energy; Titanium; Titanium dioxide; Oxidation",,,,,,"Lewis, N.S., Nocera, D.G., Powering the planet: Chemical challenges in solar energy utilization (2006) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 103 (43), pp. 15729-15735. , DOI 10.1073/pnas.0603395103; Lewis, N.S., Toward cost-effective solar energy use (2007) Science, 315, pp. 798-801; Pourbaix, M.J.N., (1966) Atlas of Electrochemical Equilibria in Aqueous Solutions, , 1st edn (Pergamon Press); Hwang, Y.J., Boukai, A., Yang, P.D., High density n-si/n-tio2 core/shell nanowire arrays with enhanced photoactivity (2009) Nano Lett., 9, pp. 410-415; Walter, M.G., Solar water splitting cells (2010) Chem. Rev., 110, pp. 6446-6473; Kay, A., Cesar, I., Gratzel, M., New benchmark for water photooxidation by nanostructured α-Fe 2O3 films (2006) Journal of the American Chemical Society, 128 (49), pp. 15714-15721. , DOI 10.1021/ja064380l; Sivula, K., Le Formal, F., Gratzel, M., WO3-fe2O3 photoanodes for water splitting: A host scaffold, guest absorber approach (2009) Chem. Mater., 21, pp. 2862-2867; Matsumura Michio, Morrison S.Roy, Anodic properties of n-Si and n-Ge electrodes in HF solution under illumination and in the dark (1983) Journal of electroanalytical chemistry and interfacial electrochemistry, 147 (1-2), pp. 157-166; Fan, F.R.F., Keil, R.G., Bard, A.J., Semiconductor electrodes. 48. Photo-oxidation of halides and water on N-silicon protected with silicide layers (1983) Journal of the American Chemical Society, 105 (2), pp. 220-224; Howe, A.T., Hawkins, R.T., Fleisch, T.H., Photoelectrochemical cells of the electrolyte-metal-insulator- semiconductor (Emis) configuration.1. Metal thickness and coverage effects in the pt-silicon oxide-N-si system (1986) J. Electrochem. Soc., 133, pp. 1369-1375; Contractor, A.Q., Bockris, J.O.M., Investigation of a protective conducting silica film on N-Silicon (1984) Electrochimica Acta, 29 (10), pp. 1427-1434. , DOI 10.1016/0013-4686(84)87022-X; Kohl, P.A., Frank, S.N., Bard, A.J., Semiconductor electrodes.[11]Behavior of N-type and P-type single-crystal semiconductors covered with thin normal-tio2 films (1977) J. Electrochem. Soc., 124, pp. 225-229; Suleymanov, A.S., On the possibility of the transformation of solar energy to chemical energy in the electrochemical cell with photoanode CdSe/TiO2 (1991) Int. J. Hydrogen Energy, 16, pp. 741-743; Siripala, W., Ivanovskaya, A., Jaramillo, T.F., Baeck, S.H., McFarland, E.W., A CU2O/TiO2 heterojunction thin film cathode for photoelectrocatalysis (2003) Sol. Energ. Mater. Sol. C, 77, pp. 229-237; Rajeshwar, K., Kaneko, M., Yamada, A., Noufi, R.N., Photoelectrochemical oxidation of halide-ions at naked, catalytically modified, and polymer-coated N-cds electrodes in aqueous-media (1985) J. Phys. Chem., 89, pp. 806-811; Ritala, M., Leskela, M., Atomic layer epitaxy - A v